> [!WARNING]
> 本文讨论的是 Objective-C 时代的 ReactiveCocoa (RAC) 实践。虽然技术栈已转向 Swift/Combine，但其中的内存管理与设计模式思维依然具有参考价值。
After much anticipation, we finally adopted RAC code in our new project. I used RAC extensively in a previous project without much consideration for its side effects. Now, finally using it in a large project, however, performance optimization reveals that the performance gains from RAC warrant rethinking.

I won't go into the details of RAC's internal implementation and code architecture, as discussed online; I'll mainly focus on the problems I encountered.

These include:


A few key points:1. 循环引用。
2. KVO中的多级KayPaths
3. 代码消耗
## 循环引用
Let's examine the problem of circular references through two case studies.

### CASE ONE
Let's take a look first.`RACObserve`The implementation details and why circular references are prone to occur:

```mermaid
graph TD
    Block["Block (implicitly retains self)"] -->|Captures| Self["self"]
    Self -->|Holds| Signal["RACSignal"]
    Signal -->|Subscribes| Block

    style Block fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px
    style Self fill:#bbf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px
    style Signal fill:#bfb,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px

    linkStyle 0,1,2 stroke:red,stroke-width:2px;
```Let's first look at the implementation of RACObserve.

```objc
#define _RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) \
({ \
    __weak id target_ = (TARGET); \
    [target_ rac_valuesForKeyPath:@keypath(TARGET, KEYPATH) observer:self]; \
})

#if __clang__ && (__clang_major__ >= 8)
#define RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) _RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH)
#else
#define RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) \
({ \
    _Pragma("clang diagnostic push") \
    _Pragma("clang diagnostic ignored \"-Wreceiver-is-weak\"") \
    _RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) \
    _Pragma("clang diagnostic pop") \
})
#endif
```This code clearly shows that `self` after `Target` is inserted.

Now let's look at the following code snippet, from the official source code.

```objc
// Observes self, and doesn't stop until self is deallocated.
RACSignal *selfSignal = RACObserve(self, arrayController.items);

// Observes the array controller, and stops when self _or_ the array
// controller is deallocated.
RACSignal *arrayControllerSignal = RACObserve(self.arrayController, items);

// Observes obj.arrayController, and stops when self _or_ the array
// controller is deallocated.
RACSignal *signal2 = RACObserve(obj.arrayController, items);

@weakify(self);
RACSignal *signal3 = [anotherSignal flattenMap:^(NSArrayController *arrayController) {
// Avoids a retain cycle because of RACObserve implicitly referencing
// self.
@strongify(self);
return RACObserve(arrayController, items);
}];
```

Official Explanation> Creates a signal which observes 
`KEYPATH` on `TARGET` for changes.
In either case, the observation continues until `TARGET` _or self_ is
deallocated. If any intermediate object is deallocated instead, it will be
assumed to have been set to nil.
Make sure to `@strongify(self)` when using this macro within a block! The
macro will _always_ reference `self`, which can silently introduce a retain
cycle within a block. As a result, you should make sure that `self` is a weak
reference (e.g., created by `@weakify` and `@strongify`) before the
expression that uses `RACObserve`In short, the `RACObserve` method was used within a `RAC` block, and then `@strongify` was not used again (i.e., it underwent a weak-to-strong transformation), resulting in the `retain` cycle.

### CASE TWO
RACSubject serves as a bridge between non-RAC and RAC environments; usage examples can be found in the GitHub tutorials.

Here's a scenario I encountered, with the code below:

```objc
@implementation UIImageView (Demo)

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url{
   return [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:nil];
}

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder{
    if (url.absoluteString.length == 0) {
        [self cancelCurrentImageLoad];
        self.image = placeholder;
        return [RACSignal empty];
    }
    RACSubject *subject = [RACSubject subject];
    if (self.frame.size.width == 0 && self.frame.size.height == 0) {
        dispatch_async(dispatch_get_main_queue(), ^{
            [self rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:subject];
        });
    }else{
        [self rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:subject];
    }
    return [subject deliverOnMainThread];
}

-(void)rbs_executeWithUrl:(NSURL*)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder subject:(RACSubject*)subject{
    [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:placeholder completed:^(UIImage * _Nullable image, NSError * _Nullable error, RBSImageCacheType cacheType, NSURL * _Nullable imageURL) {
        if(image && !error){
            [subject sendNext:image];
        }else{
            [subject sendError:error];
        }
    }];
}
@end
```

Did you spot the problem? If not, and you're unfamiliar with the implementation of RACSubject or online resources, you wouldn't understand why this part is identified as "leaky" in the Leak Profile.

The gist is that RACSubject's release is only triggered by the protocol calls to SendNext, sendError, and sendComp. From a purely code-driven perspective, this seems correct.

However, the current scenario involves asynchronous operations and the possibility of further calls. The thrown object is held by the outer layer, causing the problem of it not being actively released.

There are two possible solutions: one is for the caller to be responsible, and the other is automatic release, where the ImageView category is automatically released when it's deallocated.

Due to the project's specifics, I'll discuss the second approach here.

How is automatic release when the ImageView category is deallocated implemented?

RAC internally performs a deallocation swizz, which is triggered by a dedicated dispatch object.

The revised approach (this change also modified the lifecycle and usage of weak objects because the GCD switching call will be executed in the next main loop, which would cause problems if the current object is released)

```objc
@implementation UIImageView (Demo)

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url{
   return [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:nil];
}

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder{
    if (url.absoluteString.length == 0) {
        [self cancelCurrentImageLoad];
        self.image = placeholder;
        return [RACSignal empty];
    }
    RACSubject *subject = [RACSubject subject];
    if (self.frame.size.width == 0 && self.frame.size.height == 0) {
        _weak typeof(self) weakSelf = self;
        __weak typeof(subject) weakSubject = subject;
        dispatch_async(dispatch_get_main_queue(), ^{
            [weakSelf rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:weakSubject];
        });
    }else{
        [self rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:subject];
    }
    return [[subject deliverOnMainThread] takeUntil:self.rac_willDeallocSignal];
}

-(void)rbs_executeWithUrl:(NSURL*)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder subject:(RACSubject*)subject{
    __weak typeof(subject) weakSubject = subject;
    [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:placeholder completed:^(UIImage * _Nullable image, NSError * _Nullable error, RBSImageCacheType cacheType, NSURL * _Nullable imageURL) {
        if(image && !error){
            [weakSubject sendNext:image];
        }else{
            [weakSubject sendError:error];
        }
    }];
}
@end
```

It's this phrase, takeUntil:self.rac_WillDeallocSignal will be used to resolve the leak issue that occurred.

> [[subject deliverOnMainThread] takeUntil:self.rac_willDeallocSignal]
In summary, understanding how RACSubject works is crucial. RACSubject generates a hot signal; its internal `subscribeNext` call triggers a map operation, which then proceeds to `bind`. Internally, `bind` blocks its own operations.

In its design, RAC requires manual intervention for some operations, which can cause difficulties for beginners. While some might say it will improve after this initial period, this requires an experienced RAC programmer within the team.

## KVO中的多级KayPaths
Let's get straight to the point. As everyone knows, Cocoa's KVO only supports single-level KeyPaths, which is the current level of the Observer. Cross-level KeyPaths become more complex. RAC addresses this by solving the problem of multi-level KeyPaths. The `RACKVOWrapper` category is a multi-level implementation.

The idea is to access the next level of the KeyPath from the current level Observer, recursively, multiplying the depth until the last level of the KeyPaths. The implementation is 201 lines of code, but the related business logic involves 8 header files.

Simply put, it first needs to parse the original KeyPaths, using the runtime of the first-level KeyPath, then the next level of the KeyPath. This process is continuous, and then each level of RAC..._The parsing of propertyAttributes is stored in a collection data structure.

### 自己制造个轮子
Some might suggest using the second-to-last level of KeyPaths as the Observe and the last level as the final KeyPath in Cocoa, which would solve the problem.

However, this isn't the case. For example, if every level of the KeyPaths has already been instantiated, this works fine. But if the Observe is defined in `init`, and a certain level of another KeyPath hasn't been instantiated, the custom KVO will fail.

Another example: if all levels of the KeyPaths have been instantiated, the above solution works. But if you suddenly set a certain level of the previously constructed KeyPaths to nil and then reinitialize it, KVO will fail again.

The above solution simply won't work.

## 代码消耗
The RAC codebase is indeed quite large, with its packaged parts including C and Objective-C, and various locks for different scenarios.

The code for RAC's various business scenario layers accounts for 533KB of code across 190 files. Even for a single scenario, this represents a significant portion of the operations.

Let's talk about locks first. Locks are commonly used in the main thread, and RAC handles a wide range of locking scenarios, essentially covering all common locks.

The `RACKVOWrapper` class mentioned above involves some RAC signal-related code. Each layer of KeyPaths parsing adds another layer of overhead.

There are many business scenarios involved, so I won't list them all here. Considering only one aspect is impractical. We must address each specific business need; there's no need to use a sledgehammer to crack a nut.

## 后续
Our business logic uses RAC, which hinders our critical path performance. We've tried replacing RACObserve with KVO and blocks, but this blocks the implementation of multi-level KVO. We're considering writing our own multi-level KeyPaths solution, keeping it lightweight to address the immediate business needs for refactoring. Going forward, we'll prioritize event-driven implementations over excessive KVO, as KVO is like an iceberg in the ocean – too much is unsafe and unstable. RAC's concept is good, but it can be implemented in other ways. Without business needs, there's no technology.
